      "applicationNotes": [
        "RIPAE only covers medications during Medicare Part D's deductible period or for drugs not covered by Part D — it's not a substitute for comprehensive prescription coverage",
        "Income determines your copay percentage: lowest earners get full state coverage after $1,500 out-of-pocket, while higher earners pay 15-85% copays",
        "Experimental drugs and prescriptions older than one year are not covered by RIPAE",
        "Senior centers statewide have applications available and can provide assistance with the paperwork"
      ],
      "relatedPrograms": [
        "Medicare Extra Help (Low-Income Subsidy)",
        "Rhode Island Medicaid",
        "SNAP (Food Stamps)",
        "LIHEAP Energy Assistance"
      ],
      "contentSections": [
        {
          "type": "tier-comparison",
          "title": "Income Tiers and Coverage Levels",
          "content": "RIPAE has four income tiers that determine how much you pay:\n\n**Level 1 (Lowest Income):** Individuals $0-$23,595, Couples $0-$31,900 — State pays full cost after you spend $1,500 out-of-pocket annually\n\n**Level 2:** Individuals $23,596-$47,630, Couples $31,901-$59,558 — 40% copay after discounts\n\n**Level 3:** Individuals $47,631-$83,510, Couples $59,559-$95,261 — 70% copay after discounts\n\n**Disabled Ages 55-64:** Individual income $0-$83,510 — 15% copay after discounts\n\nNote: These 2026 figures may change — verify current limits when applying."
        }
      ],
      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Should my loved one apply for RIPAE or Medicare Extra Help first?",
          "answer": "Always check Extra Help eligibility first by calling Social Security at 1-800-772-1213. Extra Help often provides better prescription coverage than RIPAE, but you cannot have both programs. If your loved one qualifies for Extra Help, they cannot use RIPAE."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my loved one's Medicare Part D plan already covers their medications?",
          "answer": "RIPAE only helps during Part D's deductible period (before your plan's coverage kicks in) or for medications Part D doesn't cover. If Part D fully covers everything year-round, RIPAE won't provide additional benefits."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one apply if they own their home worth $200,000?",
          "answer": "Yes. RIPAE has no asset or resource test, so home value, savings accounts, and other assets don't affect eligibility. Only income matters for qualification."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my loved one's income changes after enrollment?",
          "answer": "Contact the Office of Healthy Aging at (401) 462-3000 to report income changes. Your loved one may move to a different tier with different copay percentages, but you won't lose coverage entirely unless income exceeds the maximum limits."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for RIPAE on behalf of my elderly loved one?",
          "answer": "Yes, family members can help complete and submit applications. You'll need your loved one's consent and all their personal documentation including Medicare cards, income statements, and proof of residency."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if the pharmacy says they don't accept RIPAE?",
          "answer": "Contact the Office of Healthy Aging at (401) 462-3000 if you encounter pharmacy problems. They can help coordinate with pharmacies and explain how the RIPAE discount system works with Medicare Part D plans."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long do prescriptions stay eligible for RIPAE coverage?",
          "answer": "Medications must be dispensed within one year of the prescription date. Older prescriptions are not covered, and experimental drugs are excluded regardless of when they were prescribed."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my loved one gets denied — can we appeal?",
          "answer": "Yes, you can appeal any RIPAE denial by calling the Office of Healthy Aging at (401) 462-3000. They'll review the decision and help determine if additional documentation or corrections are needed."
        }
      ],
